  <static seed="998" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/IdentifyAxisVertex100.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the axis of symmetry and vertex of the quadratic function.</p>
<p><m>{y}={-4x^{2}-12x+1}</m></p>
<p>Axis of symmetry: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p>Vertex: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>x = -{\frac{3}{2}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(-{\frac{3}{2}},10\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>This quadratic function is given in standard form. Identify that:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ a=-4,b=-12,c=1 }</m></p>
<p>To find the parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry, we use the formula <m>\displaystyle{x=-\frac{b}{2a}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  x \amp = -\frac{b}{2a} \\
   \amp = -\frac{-12}{2(-4)} \\
   \amp = {-{\frac{3}{2}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry is the line <m>\displaystyle{x={-{\frac{3}{2}}}}</m>.</p>
<p>Next, substitute <m>\displaystyle{x={-{\frac{3}{2}}}}</m> into <m>\displaystyle{{y}={-4x^{2}-12x+1}}</m>, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   y \amp = -4\left({-{\frac{3}{2}}}\right)^{2} - 12\left({-{\frac{3}{2}}}\right)+1 \\
    \amp = -4 \cdot {{\frac{9}{4}}} +{\frac{36}{2}} + 1 \\
    \amp = {10}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s vertex is at <m>\displaystyle{\left({-{\frac{3}{2}}},{10}\right)}</m>.</p>
</solution>
